05035nam a22007935i 9789814379410DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19921992si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898143794107 a10.1355/97898143794102doi  a(DE-B1597)491927  a(OCoLC)1042000847  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aBUS0230002bisacsh00aChinese Economic Activity in Netherlands India :bSelected Translations from the Dutch /ced. by M.R. Fernando, David Bulbeck. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF TABLES -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- t2. The Changing Economic Position of the Chinese in Netherlands India -- t3. Chinese Control over Rural Trade in Java in the 19 Mid-Nineteenth Century -- t4. Effects of the Revenue Farming System -- t5. The Power of Money-Lenders in Java -- t6. A Plea for Tighter Controls on Chinese Revenue Farming and Immigration -- t7. Statistical Section -- t8. The Chinese Business Community in Netherlands India -- tGLOSSARY -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe exceptional commercial success of many Southeast Asians of Chinese origin has generated much contemporary debate about the cultural or social basis of that success. This book shows that those questions have long roots in Indonesia. Dutch colonial officials in the nineteenth century expressed alarm over the rural economy. In the twentieth century more detached assessments sought to describe and explain Chinese business methods and the crucial networks they established through the Archipelago. An indispensable volume which appeared under the name of J.L Vleming used the resources of the Duth colonial taxation service to explain the nature of Chinese commercial and credit systems. This volume contains a selection of the most important writing in Dutch (by prominent lawyer Phao Liong Gie as well as by Dutch officials) that has been translated for the first time. These extracts cover the period from 1850 to 1936, though half the volume is taken from the 1926 book edited by Vleming. Basic demographic data and the revenues drawn from Chinese-held farms are presented in a statistical supplement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aBulbeck, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulbeck, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFernando, M. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernando, M.R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernando, M.R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFokkens, F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGie, Phoa Liong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVitalis, L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVleming, J. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Archive eBook-Package 1970-1999z978311060669040uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981437941040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814379410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814379410.jpg  a978-3-11-060669-0  ISEAS Archive eBook-Package 1970-1999c1970d1999  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  